<HEADLINE>
<P>
PASADENA TOURNAMENT OF ROSES MARKS ITS CENTENNIAL FESTIVAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Your series emphasized my biggest complaint with television coverage of the 
Rose Parade -- the cutting away from bands to provide commercials. 
</P>
<P>
Young people who are part of a school band are hard-working dedicated students 
who put in many hundreds of hours practicing their music, and marching 
routines. 
</P>
<P>
Receiving an invitation to march in the Rose Parade must be among the top 
recognitions those kids receive. Acceptance of such an invitation then means 
extensive fund-raising to allow their participation. 
</P>
<P>
Let America see these shining examples of dedicated and deservingly proud 
youngsters. Let the "folks back home" enjoy that surge of pride when their 
hometown band marches across the screen. 
</P>
<P>
Since sponsor fees are what provide the presentation to home viewers, the 
commercials are necessary. Certainly, creative people could devise a way to 
announce their sponsorship without cutting away from the parade. 
</P>
<P>
MARILYN CALHOUN 
</P>
<P>
Montclair 
