<HEADLINE>
<P>
OCEANSIDE TASK FORCE MAPS ATTACK ON GROWING PROBLEM OF HOMELESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GENE YASUDA, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The visible increase in the homeless people who drift aimlessly along 
Oceanside's streets and find shelter in doorways has spurred city and community 
leaders to establish a task force to find the best ways to help the city's 
needy. 
</P>
<P>
The Homeless Task Force, established earlier this week, will try to coordinate 
the efforts of social agencies that serve the city's homeless, said 
Councilwoman Lucy Chavez, who presented the group's objectives on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The 15-member task force, which includes representatives from social agencies 
and religious and business leaders, hopes to identify the specific needs of the 
different groups of people that constitute the city's homeless population, said 
Chavez, the group's chairwoman. 
</P>
<P>
"There are various types of homeless people, various degrees of homelessness," 
Chavez said. "There are the migrant workers, the street people, homeless 
families, homeless teen-agers, the mentally ill and those who have drug 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
"There are various reasons why people become homeless, and they have to be 
treated separately," she said. "There is no one solution." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Won't Replace Agencies 
</P>
<P>
The city's task force has no plans to take over existing agencies or finance 
homeless services, Chavez said. But it will assist such agencies in finding 
funds to expand and help establish a list of short- and long-term priorities. 
</P>
<P>
"If we can figure out a way to immediately help, say the homeless street 
people, especially with the recent cold weather, we will," Chavez said. "But 
the task force was not established to be a Band-Aid. This will be a long, 
analytical study to find a long-term solution, not a quick fix." 
</P>
<P>
For example, task force members are likely to consider establishing 
"transitional housing" in the city, Chavez said. 
</P>
<P>
Such housing plans provide homeless people with temporary residences and often 
special assistance to enable them to regain autonomy. Transitional housing can 
include medical care, counseling, child care and job-training programs, Chavez 
explained. 
</P>
<P>
"We're not interested in the quick fix where we house them overnight and kick 
them out the next day," Chavez said. "For those people that can be 
rehabilitated, we want to find a way to get them back into the mainstream and 
be productive." 
</P>
<P>
The group's immediate goal is to assess the size and composition of the city's 
homeless population, which is believed to have increased in recent years. The 
task force's inaugural meeting is scheduled for Jan. 30. 
</P>
<P>
"We don't have any statistics" about the size of the homeless population, she 
said, "but you can see the homeless street people sleeping under door fronts 
and under bridges. We're getting more phone calls from people concerned or 
complaining about the homeless." 
</P>
<P>
Obtaining such statistical information is necessary to receive state or federal 
assistance, said Councilwoman Melba Bishop, who is also on the task force. 
</P>
<P>
"We intend to find as many funding sources as possible," Bishop said. "But, 
when we apply, the first thing we'll be asked is, 'How did you document your 
need?' If we can't tell them, we won't be getting any money." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011489-0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 5254 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 14, 1989, Saturday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 3; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
451 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAGON PENN'S FATHER ARRESTED BY U.S. AGENTS IN DRUG PROBE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By H. G. REZA, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thomas Penn, father of Sagon Penn, was arrested Friday by federal undercover 
agents after allegedly agreeing to sell them 3 pounds of rock cocaine for 
$54,000. 
</P>
<P>
Special Agent in Charge Charlie Hill, who heads the San Diego office of the 
Drug Enforcement Administration, said Penn, 50, was arrested outside his Logan 
Avenue apartment when he demanded the money from agents sitting inside an 
unmarked car. Hill said 12 people were arrested in the case, which stemmed from 
a federal indictment that will remain sealed until the suspects are arraigned 
in U. S. District Court next week. Penn was named in the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
According to Hill, Penn and five other suspects were arrested at Penn's 
apartment. Agents recovered about 3 pounds of rock cocaine and 3 pounds of 
cocaine powder at Penn's residence, Hill said. Although one suspect was armed 
with a .22-caliber handgun and agents found a .38-caliber revolver in Penn's 
apartment, the arrests occurred without incident, said Hill. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Federal Penalty 
</P>
<P>
Normally, the federal penalty for possessing more than 50 grams of rock cocaine 
with intent to sell is 10 years to life in prison and up to $4 million in 
fines. But a recently enacted federal Omnibus Crime bill doubles that penalty 
because the cocaine was being sold within 1,000 feet of a school, in this case 
Knox Elementary, Hill said. 
</P>
<P>
Hill declined to release any more details of the case because the indictment is 
still under seal, but said that Penn and the others had been under 
investigation for some time. He said that agents were sent to Penn's apartment 
to arrest several people named in the indictment. When they arrived, they 
negotiated with Penn to purchase 3 pounds of rock cocaine, Hill said. 
</P>
<P>
The agents reported that Penn instructed them to leave for a while and return 
later after he and other accomplices finished converting cocaine powder to rock 
cocaine. When the agents returned, Penn walked outside and asked agents inside 
an unmarked car to pay him $54,000 for the rock cocaine, Hill said. Penn and 
five others in the apartment were promptly arrested. 
</P>
<P>
Clyde L. Spears, 36, identified by Hill as a gang member, is alleged to be 
Penn's drug source. Spears was among the suspects arrested. 
</P>
<P>
Penn's son, Sagon Penn, was found not guilty in 1987 in the March 31, 1985, 
shooting that left one policeman dead and another policeman and a civilian 
wounded. Two juries found that the policemen had provoked the incident by using 
racial slurs and unnecessary force when they stopped Penn for questioning. 
</P>
<P>
After Sagon Penn's arrest and during his two sensational trials, Thomas Penn 
repeatedly called for better relations between police and black residents of 
Southeast San Diego. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
