<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRIAL OPENS IN KIDNAPING OF BOY LATER FOUND DEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By UPI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LAS VEGAS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A data processor from San Diego killed a 7-year-old Mountain View, Calif., boy 
at a Stateline gambling resort 14 months ago, a district court jury was told 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Mel Harmon, Clark County chief deputy district attorney, said during opening 
statements in the murder trial of Howard Lee Haupt that he will call witnesses 
who will identify the defendant as the man last seen with the victim. 
</P>
<P>
Haupt, 38, a computer processing analyst, is accused of first-degree murder and 
first-degree kidnaping in the 1987 slaying of Alexander Harris. 
</P>
<P>
The boy vanished during the Thanksgiving holiday weekend from the video arcade 
at Whiskey Pete's Casino in Stateline, 43 miles southwest of Las Vegas near the 
California state line. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Body Found 
</P>
<P>
His body was found a month later under a trailer in the resort's employee 
housing area. 
</P>
<P>
Haupt has pleaded innocent. 
</P>
<P>
"The defense case will prove that this man had nothing whatsoever to do with 
the kidnaping and murder," defense attorney Steve Stein said during his opening 
remarks. 
</P>
<P>
Stein described Haupt as a stable, quiet, college graduate, who had never been 
arrested or investigated by law enforcement agencies. 
</P>
<P>
Harmon was expected to argue that a combination of circumstantial, direct and 
medical evidence, coupled with logic, should tell jurors that the person who 
abducted Harris and the person who killed the boy are one and the same. Harmon 
said a casino security department videotape would show the boy leaving the 
arcade with a man who looks like Haupt. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Will Attack Reliability 
</P>
<P>
Stein said he will concentrate a major portion of the defense on attacking the 
reliability of the state's eyewitness identifications. He said the defense 
intends to call at least one identification expert to refute their testimony. 
</P>
<P>
He said he will also call as many as four alibi witnesses who will testify that 
Haupt, a member of San Diego's Western Land Yacht Club, was preparing his boat 
for a land sailing competition in the desert outside Stateline about the same 
time Harris vanished from the game room. 
</P>
</TEXT>
