<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOSEPH N. BELL: IN WINTER, THE BEACH BELONGS TO US AGAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOSEPH N. BELL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is a sparkling, crackling clear day between the rains. I top the rise on 
Marguerite Street and the Pacific is suddenly spread out before me -- the 
closest I'll ever come in this life to infinity. 
</P>
<P>
This is a Thursday, 2 hours past noon, midwinter. A few months from now, 
parking will be hard to find on the street above the beach in Corona del Mar, 
there will be a profusion of out-of-state license plates, and the sand will be 
crawling with people in sunglasses dragging deck chairs and small children. But 
today, the beach belongs to the natives. It's ours in the winter -- at least 
those of us who can look up from work long enough to discover we can have this 
magnificence almost all to ourselves. 
</P>
<P>
On the grassy rim above the beach, the regulars have set up shop. An elderly 
couple in His and Her lawn chairs, reading books and communicating through 
their silence. Joggers, breathing hard, who have stopped to rest and immerse 
themselves in the view. Other portable chairs are scattered along the grass, 
mostly inhabited by older people reading but with folks just sitting and 
looking. 
</P>
<P>
There is much to see. The winter rains have momentarily washed away the smog 
with which we shroud ourselves, and it's startling to realize what it could be 
like if we stopped fouling our own atmosphere. Santa Catalina Island in its 
full length stands out in sharp bas-relief, breathtaking in its size and 
proximity, like a lost continent that appears once or twice a year to entice 
us. From above, the beach looks almost entirely deserted, a vast expanse of 
sand broken only by multiple refuse containers, fire pits, and two small boys 
kicking a soccer ball while their mother idles along behind. 
</P>
<P>
I drive down to the parking lot -- no fee on winter weekdays -- and find the 
look from above is deceptive. The beach just looks deserted; actually, there is 
much life here. It just has to be seen up close. As I park, several hundred 
nervous gulls on the sand in front of me scramble, like a crazed air squadron 
on instant alert. They settle down again 100 yards away, awaiting the next sign 
of danger. A pickup truck pulls up beside me in the almost deserted parking 
lot, and two men in work clothes get out. They have a bag from a fast-food 
restaurant, and they head across the sand, leaving a large, shaggy dog in the 
cab watching them forlornly. 
</P>
<P>
I walk down to the seawall that parallels the boat channel to the open sea. The 
sun is deceptive; it proffers warmth but the wind takes it away, gusting and 
swirling with a real cutting edge. The water in the channel is turbulent, 
slapping angrily at the seawall. For the first time in my memory, there are no 
boats in the channel. 
</P>
<P>
But people walk here, some of them bracing against the wind, some oblivious to 
it. A white-haired man in a Windbreaker emerges from the rocks with his small 
grandson who struggles along behind; they are in earnest and animated 
conversation. Two sets of lovers come into view, one young and in blue jeans, 
the other middle-aged and in street clothes. The older couple sits on a ledge 
behind the seawall, talking quietly, ignoring the wind. The younger couple 
climbs out on the jetty, hand-in-hand. A young blond woman is standing atop a 
rock overlooking the beach, holding a small dog in one hand and trying 
unsuccessfully to hold her skirt in the howling wind with the other. 
</P>
<P>
Three people, unconnected, walk alone near the shoreline: a young man, a 
middle-aged woman and an older woman. All are walking slowly, hands deep in 
their pockets, mostly looking down at the sand. Two young women in office 
attire take off their shoes and step gingerly into the sand, deep in 
conversation. The water, breaking over the beach, is subdued, grayish blue, 
looking a little angry and surly in the bright sun. 
</P>
<P>
I study Catalina and remember that, as a boy in the Midwest, I was told that if 
I dug a hole deep enough I would emerge in China -- a project I tried 
unsuccessfully a number of times. I wonder if Orange County kids are told that 
if they could swim far enough they would reach China. If so, on this day, they 
could easily believe that Catalina is China -- or maybe kids don't fantasize 
such things any more. 
</P>
<P>
As I get back to my car, a van pulls up and three Asian men -- dressed against 
the elements -- get out. They talk excitedly as they assemble a complex maze of 
fishing gear, then set out across the sand, meeting the workers returning from 
their sack lunch. 
</P>
<P>
I wish I had brought a book and a lawn chair, but instead I must get to work. 
But I'll be back. Not in the summer when a few square inches of sand are hard 
to come by, but in the winter when we have this glorious beach to ourselves and 
can watch it change character with the weather and time of day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
